e and superior to those obtained by the currently available standard techniques.Introduction Rheological characteristics and flowing law of non-Newtonian fluids are often encountered in the petroleum industry problems. The selection for constitutive equations and determination for rheological parameters are the basic elements for the research on non-Newtonian fluid, which is important for drilling optimization, hydraulic calculation and parameters optimization, etc. The standard API methods for drilling hydraulics assume either a Bingham plastic or power law rheological model, which were presented separately by Bingham (1916) and Ostwald (1925). Herschel \& Bulkley (1926) presented a yield power law model. Then, Zamora (1974), Cementing research section (1983) and Zhan (2000) published their papers to discuss the application of this model. Casson (1957) presented an improved model, which was discussed by Chen (1982), Zhong (1987) and Luo (1996), etc. Robertsion and Stiff (1976) presented a new model for drilling fluid and cement slurry. There were several papers published to discuss this model (Liu 1982, Huang 1982, etc). Bai (1980) presented a new hyperbolic model of yield-pseudoplastic fluids. After Sisko (1985) presented a new rheology model, Bailey \& Peden (1997, 2000) presented the hydraulic calculation procedures of this model. Pilehvari \& Serth (2001) introduced a rational polynomial model and the hydraulic calculation method. These models and the corresponding hydraulic calculations do provide a way for fair estimates of hydraulics for conventional wells using simple drilling fluids. However, nowadays, with many wells drilled deep, slim, or horizontal on shore and off shore using complex mud with unusual behavior, it is necessary to use more powerful rheological models and more rigorous calculation methods.},
