  abstract = {Since the pioneering work of Bingham and Schwedoff early this century
(Markovitz 1 985), many fluids of industrial significance have been shown
to exhibit flow properties intermediate between those of a solid and a
liquid. When the applied stress is less than a certain critical stress, the yield
stress, such fluids do not flow but deform plastically like a solid with
definite strain recovery upon the removal of stress. When the yield stress
is exceeded the fluid flows like a truly viscous material with finite viscosity.
This important class of fluids, known for their viscoplastic behavior,
encompasses quite a wide range of materials including concentrated suspensions,
pastes, foodstuffs, emulsions, foams, and composites (Bird et al
1 983, Utracki 1 988). Although a large amount of work (mainly experimental)
has been carried out, our knowledge on viscoplastic fluids is still
fairly fragmented as compared to other more recently developed systems
such as polymer solutions and polymer melts.
The past decade has seen a rapid development of new materials and new
technologies where there has been an increasing interest in the fundamental study of the rheology of fiber suspensions and solid-filled polymeric systems
(Metzner 1 985, Utracki 1 988). This change in emphasis in research
on fluid mechanics and rheology has brought together the well established
and matured field of polymer rheology and the more empirical area of
suspension rheology. Already the sophisticated measurement techniques
and instruments previously employed for examining viscoelasticity in polymers
have now been used to characterize the viscoplastic behavior in
composite materials. The high sensitivity of modern viscometric instruments
has made possible measurement of fluid properties at small deformations
in the stress region near or below the yield stress, where the
behavior has not been well quantified previously. This however has also
led to the discovery that some fluids, that have long been used as model
viscoplastic materials do not possess a true yield stress if the measurement
is made at vanishingly small shear rates (Barnes \& Walters 1 985). The
controversy over the existence of the yield stress however is not new, but
has persisted since the time Bingham and Green discovered that paint was
not a truly viscous liquid (Bingham \& Green 1 920, Green 1 920, Bingham
1 922). It was pointed out by these workers, and as more recent experimental
evidence (Wildemuth \& Williams 1985) has shown, that flow property
measurements for this class of fluid at low shear rates (or shear
stresses) are more frequently affected by instrumental effects than those
for simple liquids. Nevertheless, even if one accepts the notion that some
materials do have a true yield stress, measurements of this property usually
produce conflicting results depending on the techniques employed, the
criterion on which the yield stress is based, and often the patience of the
investigator as well (Hartnett \& Hu 1 989, Astarita 1 990).
This review attempts to provide the reader with an up-to-date description
of the existing methods for characterizing the rheology of visco plastic
fluids. Like other classes of materials, one can characterize a yield stress
fluid by means of appropriate constitutive equations (flow models) or by
a carefully obtained set of viscometric data using sound experimental
techniques. Since the yield stress is the most important property here, we
endeavor to give an appraisal of the available techniques for its measurement
and to discuss the complicating role of the yield stress in the measurement
of other rheological properties.},
