, however it slightly over predicts required cuttings transport velocity. Rubiandini‟s model seems to predict high flow rate required for cuttings transport. However, for the vertical case, the predicted rate seems to coincide with flow rates typical in operations. The main advantage of Rubiandini‟s model is that in his work, he considered RPM as a variable that could affect the cuttings transport. The results also indicate that Larsen‟s model and Rubiandini‟s model show the opposite effect on required cuttings transport velocity when the cuttings size is a variable parameter. In the Larsen‟s model, smaller cuttings required higher flow velocity to be transported, while inthe Rubiandini‟s model, the opposite is observed, namely larger cuttings need a higher flow velocity for transport in the wellbore. In the conclusion, several recommendations on how to achieve better cuttings transport and hole cleaning are listed.},
