p in the constrained space. The knowledge of rheological data and methods of predicting pressure losses are the key points to calculate proper pump rates and avoid any obstacle in a normal operation of oil production. Traditionally, friction pressure calculations are useful in determining horsepower requirements, bottomhole treating pressure, and maximum wellhead pressure. An accurate prediction of the friction losses is very important from the economic point of view. Optimizing the friction pressure loss calculations through the well bore annulus allows making an appropriate evaluation of the wellbore hydraulics, which is essential to reduce the problems and avoid high costs of operation.The purpose of this study is to investigate the effects of pipe eccentricity on friction pressure loss calculations for the flow of Newtonian and non-Newtonian fluids through concentric and fully eccentric annuli. The paper examines the effect of gel concentration on friction pressure losses for concentric and eccentric annuli. From data gathered by pumping various drilling and stimulation fluids through rough annuli, practical engineering correlations for Newtonian and Non-Newtonian fluids in laminar and turbulent flow regimes are developed. The results show that friction pressure losses in eccentric annuli can be considerably overestimated if the eccentricity effects are not taken into consideration.LITERATURE REVIEWA great number of studies are available on estimating friction pressure losses in laminar and turbulent flow of Newtonian and non-Newtonian fluids in concentric annuli. However, very little has been accomplished for the estimation of friction losses in laminar and turbulent flow of Newtonian and non-Newtonian fluids through eccentric annuli.},
