  volume = {In Review},
  abstract = {For the purpose of improving CFD models of particle transport in wellbore flows, i.e. cuttings transport, we have extended the Lagrangian Discrete-Particle-Model model of the commercial code ANSYS Fluent 17.2 to describe the motion of a particle settling in a shear-thinning, mildly viscoelastic orthogonal shear flow. Essentially, the fluid strain rate as the magnitude of the fluid deformation rate tensor is corrected by a particle-induced shear rate. This corrected strain rate is used to compute an apparent viscosity. The fluid is treated as a Generalized Newtonian Fluid using Cross and Carreau material functions. Different drag laws are investigated, including one which accounts for the fluids viscoelastic wake structure behavior via a correction term. We validate the model with eight different particle trajectories representing different combinations of particle diameters, fluid flow rates and rheological properties (water and polymeric solutions) provided by Khatibi et al (2016) [1].
