pipe transient show an excessive Richardson annular effect in the case of shear-thinning fluids, which
is reduced significantly in the case of shear-thickening fluids. Present results also show that the shearthickening
behavior leads to more rapid attenuation of the fluid transient. Moreover, shear-thickening
effects give rise to excessive pipeline packing which results in a pressure rise at the valve that could significantly
exceed the theoretical maximum predicted by the inviscid Joukowsky pressure rise.},
