  title = {Calculation of {{Drillpipe Rotation Effects}} on {{Fluids}} in {{Axial Flow}}: {{An Engineering Approach}}},
  abstract = {The usefulness of drill pipe rotation in drilling and cementation has been debated over the past several years. In recent years, the positive effects of pipe rotation on hole cleaning, particularly in highly-deviated wellbores, has been noted. However, many engineers are unsure of the usefulness of drill pipe rotation because the effect has not been quantified. One reason for this is that the effect of drill pipe rotation on non-Newtonian drilling fluids in annular flow is not a well understood phenomenon. There has been no single, valid method developed to mathematically characterize rotation effects on point velocities for non-Newtonian fluids in axial flow. In this paper, the effect of drill string rotation on axial flow is investigated from a fluid dynamics perspective. Using the Herschel-Bulkley rheological model, calculations for pure laminar flow and rotation are coupled to obtain shear rate characterization across the annulus. Developed first for fluids in concentric flow, these methods will be later expanded to handle the effects of drill pipe rotation in eccentric geometries. Using this method to mathematically characterize the effect of drill string rotation on axial velocity can lead to better understanding of annular flow behavior under normal drilling and circulating conditions. Areas such as hole cleaning in high angle wellbores, rotation speeds necessary to effect good annular cleanup prior to cementing, etc., will find useful application for this mathematical modeling technique. Moreover, in today’s complex wells where a narrow operating window exists between pore pressure and fracture gradients, any improved understanding of factors that change annular pressure drop and velocity patterns can be critical to the success of the drilling operation.},
