  doi = {10.2118/28304-MS},
  abstract = {AbstractFrictional pressure loss calculations in narrow annuli of slim-hole and coiled tubing operations require more accuracy than before. The paper describes a method to calculate pressure losses that better represents actual annular configurations.The skewed (vertical wells, varying eccentricity) and uniformly eccentric (deviated wells) geometries are addressed. Easy to use realistic correlations are obtained for laminar, transition and turbulent flow regimes. Experimental flow loop data validate model predictions. A step-by-step procedure is included for field calculations.IntroductionSlimhole drilling and coiled tubing operations involve fluid flow in narrow annular geometries. As field experience and theoretical calculations have shown, decreasing annular clearance completely modifies the distribution of pressure losses in a well : contrary to conventional drilling, the major part of pump pressure-more than 80\% when inner to outer diameter ratio exceeds 0.8-is lost to friction in the annulus. As the resulting equivalent circulating densities (ECD) are much higher than those in conventional wells, formation can be exposed to excessive pressures. Wellbore stability becomes, therefore, an important issue when defining parameters governing annular flow.The current practices for efficient hole cleaning consist of increasing flow rate and/or fluid rheology, which in both cases give higher ECD. In conventional drilling the increase in ECD by annular pressure losses is usually small compared to the hydrostatic pressure gradient. So, wellbore stability and efficient hole cleaning can be guaranteed by independent choices on mud density on the one hand and flow properties on the other,In narrow annular spaces, however, high annular pressure losses may result in ECD values close to or higher than formation fracture gradient. Accurate modeling of annular pressure losses is therefore needed in order to successfully adjust fluid density and rheology to the whole set of drilling parameters.Annular pressure losses depend on fluid rheology, flow regime and the geometry of the annulus, Previous models treat either concentric or eccentric annuli and assume uniformity along the wellbore.Concentric annular flow has received considerable attention, At laminar flow conditions exact models are available for Newtonian, power law and Bingham plastic fluids, Recently, Reed and Pilehvari proposed a model for laminar, transitional and turbulent flows. This model extends well established results on Newtonian and non-Newtonian pipe flow-in particular Dodge and Metzner's work to concentric annular flow.Models also exist for uniformly eccentric annuli in laminar flow, analytical for Newtonian and numerical for non-Newtonian fluids.P. 113\^},
